[0m[49m[39m  164, 180[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  165, 181[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 166     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 1: Image quality validation.** Before spending compute on inference, verify the submitted image is actually usable. A blurry photo, an image that's too dark, or one where no lesion is visible will produce garbage predictions. This step catches those early and returns actionable feedback to the submitter. The quality check is lightweight (basic image statistics, not a full ML model) and runs in milliseconds. Skip this step and you'll waste inference costs on unusable images while returning meaningless confidence scores that erode clinician trust.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Image upload and metadata stripping.** Patient-submitted smartphone photos contain EXIF metadata including GPS coordinates that reveal home addresses, device serial numbers, and photographer names. Before storing the image or running any analysis, strip all non-essential metadata. Retain only the timestamp and image dimensions. This is a privacy requirement, not an optimization. Skip this step and you're storing patient home addresses alongside their medical photographs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION strip_and_store(image_bytes, patient_id):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate file type by checking magic bytes, not just the extension.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Enforce maximum file size at the API Gateway level (e.g., 10 MB).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF NOT valid_image_magic_bytes(image_bytes):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN { error: "Invalid file type. Please upload a JPEG or PNG image." }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Strip EXIF metadata. Remove GPS, device IDs, photographer info.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Keep only timestamp and dimensions for clinical context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     stripped_image = remove_exif_metadata(image_bytes, keep=["DateTime", "ImageWidth", "ImageHeight"])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store the stripped image in S3 with encryption.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image_key = "lesion-images/{date}/{patient_id}/{unique_id}.jpg"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     upload to S3 bucket with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         key                = image_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         body               = stripped_image
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         server_side_encryption = "aws:kms"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN { image_key: image_key, original_bytes: stripped_image }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Image quality validation.** Before spending compute on inference, verify the submitted image is actually usable. A blurry photo, an image that's too dark, or one where no lesion is visible will produce garbage predictions. This step catches those early and returns actionable feedback to the submitter. The quality check is lightweight (basic image statistics, not a full ML model) and runs in milliseconds. Skip this step and you'll waste inference costs on unusable images while returning meaningless confidence scores that erode clinician trust.
[0m[49m[39m  167, 206[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  168, 207[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  169, 208[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION validate_image_quality(image_bytes):
[0m[49m[39m  170, 209[0m:[39m[49m     // Load the image and compute basic quality metrics.
[0m[49m[39m  171, 210[0m:[39m[49m     // These are fast statistical checks, not ML inference.
[0m[49m[39m  172, 211[0m:[39m[49m     image = decode_image(image_bytes)
[0m[49m[39m  173, 212[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  174, 213[0m:[39m[49m     // Check 1: Resolution. The model needs enough pixels to see lesion detail.
[0m[49m[39m  175, 214[0m:[39m[49m     // Below 224x224 (typical model input size), there's not enough information.
[0m[49m[39m  176, 215[0m:[39m[49m     width, height = image.dimensions
[0m[49m[39m  177, 216[0m:[39m[49m     IF width < 224 OR height < 224:
[0m[49m[39m  178, 217[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN { valid: false, reason: "Image resolution too low. Please move closer to the lesion." }
[0m[49m[39m  179, 218[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  180, 219[0m:[39m[49m     // Check 2: Blur detection using Laplacian variance.
[0m[49m[39m  181, 220[0m:[39m[49m     // A sharp image has high variance in its edge map; a blurry one is flat.
[0m[49m[39m  182, 221[0m:[39m[49m     // Threshold calibrated on sample images; adjust based on your camera population.
[0m[49m[39m  183, 222[0m:[39m[49m     blur_score = compute_laplacian_variance(image)
[0m[49m[39m  184, 223[0m:[39m[49m     IF blur_score < 100:
[0m[49m[39m  185, 224[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN { valid: false, reason: "Image appears blurry. Please hold steady and ensure focus." }
[0m[49m[39m  186, 225[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  187, 226[0m:[39m[49m     // Check 3: Brightness. Too dark or too bright means lost detail.
[0m[49m[39m  188, 227[0m:[39m[49m     mean_brightness = compute_mean_pixel_value(image)
[0m[49m[39m  189, 228[0m:[39m[49m     IF mean_brightness < 40:
[0m[49m[39m  190, 229[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN { valid: false, reason: "Image too dark. Please improve lighting." }
[0m[49m[39m  191, 230[0m:[39m[49m     IF mean_brightness > 220:
[0m[49m[39m  192, 231[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN { valid: false, reason: "Image too bright or overexposed. Reduce direct light." }
[0m[49m[39m  193, 232[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  194, 233[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN { valid: true }
[0m[49m[39m  195, 234[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  196, 235[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 197     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 2: Image preprocessing.** The classification model expects a specific input format: fixed dimensions, normalized pixel values, and ideally a clean view of the lesion without excessive background. This step transforms the raw photograph into what the model needs. Different models have different input requirements, so the preprocessing must match the model's training pipeline exactly. If you resize differently than the training data was resized, or normalize to a different range, accuracy degrades silently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Image preprocessing.** The classification model expects a specific input format: fixed dimensions, normalized pixel values, and ideally a clean view of the lesion without excessive background. This step transforms the raw photograph into what the model needs. Different models have different input requirements, so the preprocessing must match the model's training pipeline exactly. If you resize differently than the training data was resized, or normalize to a different range, accuracy degrades silently.
[0m[49m[39m  198, 237[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  199, 238[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  200, 239[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION preprocess_image(image_bytes, target_size=224):
[0m[49m[39m  201, 240[0m:[39m[49m     // Decode and resize to the model's expected input dimensions.
[0m[49m[39m  202, 241[0m:[39m[49m     // Most classification models expect square inputs (224x224 or 299x299).
[0m[49m[39m  203, 242[0m:[39m[49m     image = decode_image(image_bytes)
[0m[49m[39m  204, 243[0m:[39m[49m     image = resize(image, target_size, target_size)
[0m[49m[39m  205, 244[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  206, 245[0m:[39m[49m     // Normalize pixel values to [0, 1] range.
[0m[49m[39m  207, 246[0m:[39m[49m     // Neural networks train on normalized inputs; raw 0-255 values would produce
[0m[49m[39m  208, 247[0m:[39m[49m     // wildly wrong activations.
[0m[49m[39m  209, 248[0m:[39m[49m     image = image / 255.0
[0m[49m[39m  210, 249[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  211, 250[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply the same channel-wise normalization used during training.
[0m[49m[39m  212, 251[0m:[39m[49m     // These values (ImageNet means and standard deviations) are standard for
[0m[49m[39m  213, 252[0m:[39m[49m     // models pre-trained on ImageNet and fine-tuned on dermatology data.
[0m[49m[39m  214, 253[0m:[39m[49m     mean = [0.485, 0.456, 0.406]  // RGB channel means from ImageNet
[0m[49m[39m  215, 254[0m:[39m[49m     std  = [0.229, 0.224, 0.225]  // RGB channel standard deviations
[0m[49m[39m  216, 255[0m:[39m[49m     image = (image - mean) / std
[0m[49m[39m  217, 256[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  218, 257[0m:[39m[49m     // Serialize to the format the inference endpoint expects.
[0m[49m[39m  219, 258[0m:[39m[49m     // SageMaker endpoints typically accept raw bytes or JSON-encoded tensors.
[0m[49m[39m  220, 259[0m:[39m[49m     payload = serialize_to_model_format(image)
[0m[49m[39m  221, 260[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  222, 261[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN payload
[0m[49m[39m  223, 262[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  224, 263[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 225     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 3: Model inference.** Send the preprocessed image to the classification model and get back a probability distribution across triage categories. The model outputs raw logits or softmax probabilities for each class. This is the core ML step, and it's also the most expensive computationally. The endpoint should respond in under 2 seconds for a good user experience. If latency is a concern at scale, consider batching or asynchronous inference for non-urgent submissions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Model inference.** Send the preprocessed image to the classification model and get back a probability distribution across triage categories. The model outputs raw logits or softmax probabilities for each class. This is the core ML step, and it's also the most expensive computationally. The endpoint should respond in under 2 seconds for a good user experience. If latency is a concern at scale, consider batching or asynchronous inference for non-urgent submissions.
[0m[49m[39m  226, 265[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  227, 266[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  228, 267[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION classify_lesion(preprocessed_payload, endpoint_name):
[0m[49m[39m  229, 268[0m:[39m[49m     // Call the SageMaker real-time inference endpoint.
[0m[49m[39m  230, 269[0m:[39m[49m     // The endpoint hosts the trained model and handles GPU allocation.
[0m[49m[39m  231, 270[0m:[39m[49m     response = call SageMaker.InvokeEndpoint with:
